skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:3:description: Create, refactor, and validate Rhei Plan markdown documents for project execution. Use when users ask for implementation plans, task breakdowns, roadmap-to-task conversion, dependency cleanup, or status updates in a strict, structured plan format with task states and prerequisites.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:8:Produce a Rhei Plan markdown document that is deterministic, dependency-safe, and ready for execution.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:15:- **Directory Workspace** — an `index.rhei.md` plus a `tasks/` directory of per-file task definitions. Use when multiple agents or humans will work the plan in parallel.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:22:- Optionally emit `**States:** <state-machine-name>` as the first non-empty line after the H1 to declare which state machine the plan follows. Omit to use the built-in `rhei` state machine.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:23:- Optionally emit a YAML frontmatter block (see *Frontmatter*) after the `**States:**` field, before any H2 section.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:30:- Emit `index.rhei.md` at the workspace root: H1, optional `**States:**`, optional frontmatter, optional H2 context sections — **no** `## Tasks` section.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:31:- Emit one or more task files under `tasks/`. Each file begins directly with `### <kind> <id>:` headers and contains no `# Rhei:` header and no independent frontmatter.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:32:- Frontmatter (including `structure`, `metadata.tasks.*`) lives only in `index.rhei.md` — the workspace has exactly one authoritative metadata map.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:33:- Prefer letter-prefixed or name-style IDs (e.g., `task-avatar`, `bug-null-cache`) over sequential numbers. Numeric IDs are safe in Single-File Plans but risk collisions in a distributed workspace.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:37:Use this exact block shape for every task node (root and child):
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:41:**State:** <state>
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:42:**Prior:** Task <id>, Task <id>
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:48:- **Every task MUST have a `**State:**` field.** A task without `**State:**` is invalid and will fail validation. This is the single most common authoring mistake — always check for it before finishing.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:49:- Keep `**State:**` as the first metadata line, directly under the task heading — no blank line between the heading and `**State:**`.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:50:- Place `**Prior:**` second when present.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:51:- Omit `**Prior:**` when no prerequisites exist.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:52:- **Do not author `**Assignee:**` or `> **Result:**` blocks.** Both are runtime-owned: `rhei next` writes `**Assignee:**` when a task is claimed, `rhei complete` removes it and writes `> **Result:** [<id>](runtime/results/<id>.md)`. The plan writer never populates these fields.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:53:- Separate metadata from description with a blank line.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:54:- Emit no other metadata fields.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:57:### Allowed States
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:59:Run `rhei states` in the project to discover the allowed state values, their agent instructions, and the declared transitions for the state machine the plan will follow. Use `rhei states --state-machine <path>` to target a specific YAML file (for example, the one referenced by a plan's `**States:**` line), and `rhei states --json` when machine-readable output is preferred. Use only state values reported by that command, follow the printed instructions when describing task work, and respect the declared transitions when choosing initial states.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:61:If the `rhei` CLI is unavailable in the project, fall back to reading the state machine YAML file directly (typically `docs/states.yaml`, or the file referenced by `**States:**`). If the project does not define its own state machine, fall back to the default Rhei state set documented in [default-states.md](references/default-states.md).
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:63:Each node's initial state comes from the machine's `profiles.<name>.initial` via `node_policy` — **not** from a state-level `initial: true` flag. In the built-in `rhei` machine, the initial state is `draft`. When authoring a new plan under that machine, every task starts in `draft`.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:68:**State:** `agent-review`
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:69:**State:** `human review`
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:70:**State:** `security.review-2`
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:87:Decompose a task with nested `Task` nodes at a deeper heading level. Child nodes use the same block shape as roots but with a dotted id that extends the parent:
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:90:#### Task <parent>.<child>: <title>
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:91:**State:** <state>
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:97:- **Every child task MUST have a `**State:**` field.** Same rule as for root tasks.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:98:- Keep `**State:**` as the first line directly under the heading — no blank line between the heading and `**State:**`.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:99:- The child id extends the parent id by exactly one new segment, separated by `.`: `1.1`, `1.2.3`, `api.cache`.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:100:- Numeric children increment from `1` within their parent; named children use short identifiers. Mixed numeric/named segments are allowed as long as depth matches.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:101:- Sibling ids must be unique under the same parent.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:102:- Default to adding child tasks whenever a task benefits from progressive disclosure and per-step logging. Skip them only when the work is clearly atomic.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:103:- When skipping child tasks, make the task description explicit enough to act as a single implementation log entry.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:104:- Heading depth is bounded by the plan's `structure.maxLevels` (default `2`, maximum `4`). H3 is depth 1, H4 is depth 2, H5 is depth 3, H6 is depth 4. A plan that needs more than two levels must declare `structure.maxLevels` in frontmatter.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:108:Emit a YAML frontmatter block only when the plan needs non-default `structure` settings. The `structure` block is the only thing a plan writer should author in frontmatter; runtime-managed keys under `metadata.tasks.*` (such as `stateVisits` counters) are written by the CLI and must not be hand-authored.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:112:structure:
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:113:  maxLevels: 3
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:114:  nodeKinds: [task, bug]
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:118:- `structure.maxLevels` — maximum task depth, from `1` (`###` only) through `4` (`######` allowed). Default `2`. Required when any child task would exceed depth 2.
skills/rhei-plan-writer/SKILL.md:119:- `structure.nodeKinds` — allowed heading keywords. Default `[task]`. Add other kinds (`bug`, `spike`, `epic`, ...) only when the plan actually uses them. The keyword `rhei` is reserved and must never appear in `nodeKinds`.
